Year = {{2016}},
Volume = {{11}},
Pages = {{63-82}},
Month = {{APR}},
Abstract = {{Neuroimaging of the domestic dog is a rapidly expanding research topic
   in terms of the cognitive domains being investigated. Because dogs have
   shared both a physical and social world with humans for thousands of
   years, they provide a unique and socially relevant means of
   investigating a variety of shared human and canine psychological
   phenomena. Additionally, their trainability allows for neuroimaging to
   be carried out noninvasively in an awake and unrestrained state. In this
   review, a brief overview of functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI)
   is followed by an analysis of recent research with dogs using fMRI.
   Methodological and conceptual concerns found across multiple studies are
   raised, and solutions to these issues are suggested. With the research
   capabilities brought by canine functional imaging, findings may improve
   our understanding of canine cognitive processes, identify neural
   correlates of behavioral traits, and provide early-life selection
   measures for dogs in working roles.}},
